<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Real Life Scenarios</h1>
    </header>

    <section class="example">
        <h2>Case Study: Google and BeyondCorp</h2>
        <p>Google pioneered the Zero Trust approach through its <strong>BeyondCorp</strong> initiative, which shifted security away from network location and toward user and device authentication. Employees must verify their identity and the health of their device before accessing any system. This model has allowed Google to reduce its reliance on VPNs and maintain high levels of security even during major cyber threats.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="example">
        <h2>Hypothetical Scenario: A Hospital Thwarts a Breach</h2>
        <p>In a modern hospital using Zero Trust Architecture, an external attacker attempts to gain access to patient records. Despite acquiring a staff member’s password, the system immediately flags the login attempt due to unverified device status and unusual location. Access is denied, and an alert is triggered, allowing IT staff to respond instantly — preventing data theft and maintaining patient privacy.</p>
    </section>

